      <item>
        <title>Skewness</title>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;third momentum of returns:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex; mode=display&quot;&gt;t = x - mean(x)&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex; mode=display&quot;&gt;m = mean(t ^ 3)&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex; mode=display&quot;&gt;s = mean(t ^ 2)&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex; mode=display&quot;&gt;skewness = \frac{m}{s^{\frac{3}{2}}}&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;p&gt;positive skewness indicates a &lt;code&gt;right tail&lt;/code&gt; and the mass of the data on the left (&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;% &lt;![CDATA[
&lt; \mu %]]&gt;&lt;/script&gt;);&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;negative skewness indicates a &lt;code&gt;left tail&lt;/code&gt; and the mass of the data on the right (&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;&gt; \mu&lt;/script&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
        <pubDate>Tue, 29 Mar 2016 00:44:01 +0200</pubDate>
        <link>http://codiepp.github.io/Hedge-o-Mat/Hedge-o-Mat/statistics/skewness.html</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="true">http://codiepp.github.io/Hedge-o-Mat/Hedge-o-Mat/statistics/skewness.html</guid>
        
        
        <category>statistics</category>
        
      </item>
    
      <item>
        <title>Kurtosis</title>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;fourth momentum of returns:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex; mode=display&quot;&gt;t = x - mean(x)&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex; mode=display&quot;&gt;m = mean(t ^ 4)&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex; mode=display&quot;&gt;s = mean(t ^ 2)&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex; mode=display&quot;&gt;kurtosis = \frac{m}{s^2}&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A normal distribution has a kurtosis of 3.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If kurtosis &amp;lt; 3 then the distribution is &lt;code&gt;platykurtic&lt;/code&gt; (looks flatter than normal distr., more mass in the centre, has smaller tails),&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;if kurtosis &amp;gt; 3 then the disitribution is said to be &lt;code&gt;leptokurtic&lt;/code&gt; (more peaked than normal distr. and larger tails!).&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
        <pubDate>Tue, 29 Mar 2016 00:44:01 +0200</pubDate>
        <link>http://codiepp.github.io/Hedge-o-Mat/Hedge-o-Mat/statistics/kurtosis.html</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="true">http://codiepp.github.io/Hedge-o-Mat/Hedge-o-Mat/statistics/kurtosis.html</guid>
        
        
        <category>statistics</category>
        
      </item>
    
      <item>
        <title>Jarque-Bera test (JB)</title>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;Tests whether a distribution of a random variable follows the normal distribution. Thus, whether its third and fourth moments, the &lt;a href=&quot;skewness.html&quot;&gt;skewness&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;kurtosis.html&quot;&gt;kurtosis&lt;/a&gt;, are equal to the values of a normal distribution: skewness = 0, kurtosis = 3.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Using the error term (&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\hat{u}&lt;/script&gt;) of an OLS regression one can estimate these two parameters:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Skewness: &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;b1 = \frac{E[u^3]}{(\sigma^2)^{3/2}}&lt;/script&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kurtosis: &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;b2 = \frac{E[u^4]}{(\sigma^2)^{2}}&lt;/script&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Test statistics:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex; mode=display&quot;&gt;W = T[\frac{b_1^2}{6} + \frac{(b_2 - 3)^2}{24}]&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;p&gt;where T is the sample size.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This test statistics follows a Chi&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; distribution with two degrees of freedom Χ&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;(2).&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
        <pubDate>Tue, 29 Mar 2016 00:44:01 +0200</pubDate>
        <link>http://codiepp.github.io/Hedge-o-Mat/Hedge-o-Mat/statistics/jarque-bera-test.html</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="true">http://codiepp.github.io/Hedge-o-Mat/Hedge-o-Mat/statistics/jarque-bera-test.html</guid>
        
        
        <category>statistics</category>
        
      </item>
    
